further_info:
I plan to devote two weeks to each book but will encourage members to read ahead as Flex's <em>The Wanderer between the Two Worlds</em> is short.  I want to be able to let members know that all the readings are available on Kindle and that they can use an earlier translation of Lussu's work entitled <em>Sardinian Brigade</em>.  If they can, they could also read the originals: Flex's <em>Der Wanderer zwischen beiden</em> <em>Welten </em>and/or Lussu's <em>Un Anno Sull'Altipiano,  </em>I will limit the reading in Lussu to 100 pages each week and that in Spackman to about 70 pages each week.  I expect to lay out the background for no more than 20 minutes in each session, but rather than start with it in lecture format, bring it in as it relates to discussion prompted by the readings.  I will probably use the videos for a new start after the break.  I count on the readings as the core of the course.  Flex's book, only available in English since 2014, was outsold in interwar Germany only by Remarque's <em>All Quiet on the Western Front</em>.  Lussu's was published in Italy only after the fall of fascism and has afterward never been out of print there.  Spackman's memoir offers a rare look at a half-colonial army's engagement in a war among imperial powers; it also adds a chapter to our acquaintance with conflict in Iraq.

